ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescence intensity of N-CQDs@SiO2 in the absence and presence of NTP at different pH was studied (Fig. 3
                        ). The fluorescence emission spectra of the prepared sensor exhibited pH-dependent characterization, with strong fluorescence emission under neutral/alkaline conditions and relatively weak fluorescence emission under acidic conditions. This phenomenon is related to the deprotonation and protonation of acidic and basic groups (on N-CQDs) in-ground or excited states, which could change the property and the rate of transition processes, and finally affect the fluorescence intensity of N-CQDs@SiO2 
                        [47]. The fluorescence quenching effect of N-CQDs@SiO2 by NTP varies with pH either, with the optimum quenching effect observed at pH 7.0. Thus pH 7.0 was chosen in the subsequent experiments.
